Name: Protocol

Part 1: Preparation of DNA Storage Samples

    Step 1.1: Prepare the solutions for DNA storage.

        Option 1.1.1: Use nuclease-free water as the storage medium.
            - Component A: Nuclease-free water
            (Operational details: Ensure the water is certified nuclease-free. Use sterile, nuclease-free containers and pipette tips to handle it.)

        Option 1.1.2: Use TE buffer as the storage medium.
            - Component A: TE Buffer (1X)
                - Recipe:
                    - 10 mM Tris-HCl, pH 8.0
                    - 1 mM EDTA, pH 8.0
                    - Nuclease-free water to final volume
            (Operational details: Prepare from stock solutions of Tris and EDTA. Adjust the final pH to 8.0 using HCl. Sterilize the final solution by autoclaving or filtration through a 0.22 µm filter.)

        Option 1.1.3: Use Tris-HCl buffer as the storage medium.
            - Component A: Tris-HCl Buffer (1X)
                - Recipe:
                    - 10 mM Tris-HCl, pH 8.0
                    - Nuclease-free water to final volume
            (Operational details: Prepare from a stock solution of Tris. Adjust the final pH to 8.0 using HCl. Sterilize the final solution by autoclaving or filtration through a 0.22 µm filter.)

        Option 1.1.4: Use Phosphate-Buffered Saline (PBS) as the storage medium.
            - Component A: PBS Buffer (1X)
                - Recipe:
                    - 137 mM Sodium chloride (NaCl)
                    - 2.7 mM Potassium chloride (KCl)
                    - 10 mM Disodium phosphate (Na2HPO4)
                    - 1.8 mM Monopotassium phosphate (KH2PO4)
                    - Nuclease-free water to final volume
            (Operational details: Dissolve all salts in nuclease-free water. Adjust pH to 7.4 using HCl if necessary. Sterilize by autoclaving or filtration through a 0.22 µm filter.)

    Step 1.2: Prepare DNA aliquots for storage and analysis.
        (Operational details: This step should be performed for each storage solution prepared in Step 1.1. The goal is to create multiple identical aliquots for each condition, allowing for testing at different time points without disturbing the other samples.)

        Option 1.2.1: Create final DNA samples for storage.
            - Component A: Purified DNA stock solution (of known concentration)
            - Component B: Storage Solution (from Options 1.1.1, 1.1.2, 1.1.3, or 1.1.4)
            (Operational details: Dilute the Purified DNA stock solution with one of the storage solutions to a final target concentration (e.g., 20 ng/µL). Prepare a master mix for each condition to ensure uniformity. Dispense the final mix into multiple, clearly labeled, sterile, nuclease-free microcentrifuge tubes (e.g., 20 µL per tube). Create enough aliquots per condition to cover all planned time points, plus extras. For example, for 5 time points, create at least 6 aliquots for each storage condition.)

Part 2: Baseline Quality Assessment (Timepoint 0)

    Step 2.1: Assess initial DNA concentration and purity.
        (Operational details: Use one freshly prepared aliquot from each storage condition created in Step 1.2 for this baseline analysis.)

        Option 2.1.1: Analysis via UV-Vis Spectrophotometry.
            - Component A: DNA aliquot (in its respective storage solution)
            - Component B: Blanking Solution (the corresponding storage solution without DNA)
            (Operational details: Use a spectrophotometer (e.g., NanoDrop). Use 1-2 µL of the appropriate blanking solution to zero the instrument. Measure 1-2 µL of each DNA aliquot. Record the concentration (ng/µL), A260/280 ratio (for protein contamination assessment), and A260/230 ratio (for salt/organic solvent contamination assessment).)

    Step 2.2: Assess initial DNA integrity.

        Option 2.2.1: Analysis via Agarose Gel Electrophoresis with TAE Buffer.
            - Component A: 1% Agarose Gel
                - Recipe:
                    - Agarose
                    - 1X TAE Buffer
            - Component B: 1X TAE Running Buffer
                - Recipe:
                    - 40 mM Tris
                    - 20 mM Acetic acid
                    - 1 mM EDTA
                    - Nuclease-free water to final volume
            - Component C: DNA samples for loading
                - Recipe:
                    - DNA aliquot (e.g., 100 ng)
                    - 6X DNA loading dye
                    - Nuclease-free water (if needed to equalize volume)
            - Component D: DNA ladder
            - Component E: DNA stain
            (Operational details: Prepare the agarose gel by dissolving agarose in 1X TAE buffer via heating. Add DNA stain to the molten agarose or stain the gel post-electrophoresis. Prepare DNA samples by mixing with loading dye. Load samples and DNA ladder into the gel wells. Run the gel in 1X TAE Running Buffer at 80-120 V until dye fronts have sufficiently separated. Visualize the DNA bands under UV or blue light. Document the results by imaging the gel. Look for a sharp, high-molecular-weight band with minimal smearing.)

        Option 2.2.2: Analysis via Agarose Gel Electrophoresis with TBE Buffer.
            - Component A: 1% Agarose Gel
                - Recipe:
                    - Agarose
                    - 1X TBE Buffer
            - Component B: 1X TBE Running Buffer
                - Recipe:
                    - 89 mM Tris

                    - Nuclease-free water to final volume
            - Component C: DNA samples for loading

                    - 6X DNA loading dye
                    - Nuclease-free water (if needed to equalize volume)
            - Component D: DNA ladder
            - Component E: DNA stain
            (Operational details: Prepare the agarose gel by dissolving agarose in 1X TBE buffer via heating. Add DNA stain to the molten agarose or stain the gel post-electrophoresis. Prepare DNA samples by mixing with loading dye. Load samples and DNA ladder into the gel wells. Run the gel in 1X TBE Running Buffer at 80-120 V until dye fronts have sufficiently separated. Visualize the DNA bands under UV or blue light. Document the results by imaging the gel. Look for a sharp, high-molecular-weight band with minimal smearing.)

    Step 2.3: Assess initial DNA functionality.

        Option 2.3.1: Analysis via quantitative PCR (qPCR).
            - Component A: qPCR Reaction Mix
                - Recipe:
                    - qPCR Master Mix (containing polymerase, dNTPs, and buffer)
                    - Forward Primer (target-specific)
                    - Reverse Primer (target-specific)
                    - DNA Template (a standardized amount, e.g., 10 ng from the DNA aliquot)
                    - Nuclease-free water to final reaction volume
            (Operational details: Assemble reactions on ice in qPCR plates or tubes. Include no-template controls (NTCs) for each primer set. Run the qPCR plate on a real-time PCR instrument using an appropriate thermal cycling protocol. Record the quantification cycle (Cq) value for each sample. Lower Cq values indicate more intact, amplifiable template.)

Part 3: Sample Storage

    Step 3.1: Store the remaining DNA aliquots.

        Option 3.1.1: Long-term storage at 4 degrees Celsius.
            - Component A: Prepared DNA aliquots (from Step 1.2)
            (Operational details: Place all remaining aliquots (excluding those used for Timepoint 0 analysis) into a calibrated refrigerator set to 4°C. Arrange samples in labeled boxes. For best practice, wrap the sample boxes in foil or use opaque boxes to protect the DNA from light exposure. Maintain a log of the storage temperature.)

Part 4: Post-Storage Quality Assessment (Timepoint X)

    Step 4.1: Retrieve samples for analysis at a scheduled time point.
        (Operational details: At each planned time point (e.g., 1 week, 1 month, 6 months, 1 year), retrieve one aliquot for each storage condition from the 4°C refrigerator. Allow samples to equilibrate to room temperature before opening.)

        Option 4.1.1: Sample retrieval.
            - Component A: Stored DNA aliquot
            (Operational details: Gently vortex and briefly centrifuge the tube to collect the contents at the bottom before analysis.)

    Step 4.2: Assess post-storage DNA concentration and purity.

    Step 4.3: Assess post-storage DNA integrity.
        (Operational details: Repeat the procedure from Step 2.2, running the Timepoint 0 and current timepoint samples on the same gel for direct comparison if possible.)

        Option 4.3.1: Analysis via Agarose Gel Electrophoresis with TAE Buffer.
            - Component A: 1% Agarose Gel
                - Recipe:
                    - Agarose
                    - 1X TAE Buffer
            - Component B: 1X TAE Running Buffer

            - Component C: DNA samples for loading

            - Component D: DNA ladder

            (Operational details: Follow the operational details as described in Option 2.2.1. Compare the band intensity and presence of smearing to the Timepoint 0 gel image.)

        Option 4.3.2: Analysis via Agarose Gel Electrophoresis with TBE Buffer.
            - Component A: 1% Agarose Gel

            - Component B: 1X TBE Running Buffer

            - Component D: DNA ladder
            - Component E: DNA stain
            (Operational details: Follow the operational details as described in Option 2.2.2. Compare the band intensity and presence of smearing to the Timepoint 0 gel image.)

    Step 4.4: Assess post-storage DNA functionality.
        (Operational details: Repeat the procedure from Step 2.3.)

        Option 4.4.1: Analysis via quantitative PCR (qPCR).
            - Component A: qPCR Reaction Mix
